  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and frameworks are designed to promote cooperation among countries and establish global standards to prevent and detect money laundering activities. Key international instruments include:\n\n### 1. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) (Vienna Convention):** This was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering, focusing on the proceeds of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) (Palermo Convention):** This convention includes provisions for combating money laundering, particularly in relation to organized crime.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Corruption (2003) (Merida Convention):** This convention emphasizes the need to combat money laundering linked to corruption.\n\n### 2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental body established in 1989 to develop and promote policies to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n   - **FATF Recommendations:** The FATF\u2019s 40 Recommendations provide a comprehensive framework for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) measures. These recommendations are widely recognized as the global standard in this area.\n\n### 3. **European Union Directives**\n   - The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) to harmonize AML laws across member states. The latest, the **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**, enhances transparency and strengthens cooperation among EU countries.\n\n### 4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - The Basel Committee has issued guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering, including the \"Core Principles for Effective Banking Supervision,\" which include AML measures.\n\n### 5. **Other Regional Bodies**\n   - **Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units:** Facilitates international cooperation among financial intelligence units (FIUs) to combat money laundering.\n   - **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure, and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990):** Provides a framework for mutual legal assistance and cooperation in investigating money laundering.\n\n### Key Principles in International AML Laws:\n   - **Criminalization of Money Laundering:** Countries are required to criminalize money laundering under their domestic laws.\n   - **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Financial institutions must verify the identity of their customers and assess the risks associated with them.\n   - **Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR):** Institutions must report suspicious transactions to the relevant authorities.\n   - **International Cooperation:** Countries must assist each other in investigations, prosecutions, and asset recovery related to money laundering.\n\nWhile these international frameworks provide a basis for AML efforts, individual countries are responsible for implementing and enforcing these standards through their own legal and regulatory systems. Compliance with international AML laws is often monitored through peer reviews and mutual evaluations conducted by organizations like the FATF.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
